13/13 if nothing else, question everything. the goal isn't to make better predictions but to make fewer wrong decisions.
12/13 the irony of VC is that we invest in people that are changing their industries while forgetting to do the same to our own.
11/13 huge opp'ty for investors/groups that use a fast-follower model: beg your way into the best deals rather than searching for new ones.
10/13 ask yourself where "venture style" returns come from: the business of VC is more about deal selection than deal sourcing.
9/13 before an individual angel joins a group: reference check with founders. it's OK to pass on a deal, not OK to treat founders poorly.
8/13 angel groups aren‚Äôt bad but individual angels should beware: an angel group is only as good as it‚Äôs worst/least-reputable member.
7/13 founders are our customers: you can learn a lot about a particular investor/group by assessing the suit-to-jeans ratio across the room.
6/13 track record: all investors/groups should track portfolio performance - IRR matters. if you‚Äôve been doing it for a while, no excuses.
5/13 on value add: unless an investor/group has made it‚Äôs money in the exact same type of business, value add can be outdated or misguided.
4/13 on reputation: how long an investor/group has been around doesn‚Äôt matter, you‚Äôre only as good as your latest founder interaction.
3/13 in the past, angel groups provided proprietary deal flow & structured process. today, individual angels can accomplish both themselves.
2/13 as the cost to start tech co's drops, more angels come into the game - no surprise there. angel groups, however, must adapt or die.
1/13 on angel investing, angel groups, understanding your customer, getting into deals and (hopefully) making money‚Ä¶
